AB  - A multinational firm faced with ‘arm's length’ limitations on its transfer prices is examined, where the limitations are determined by the firm's marginal cost and intracountry prices. Such a firm is shown to manipulate its production and sales in order to gain a more desirable transfer price. Comparative static results develop policy implications not found in simpler models, which often assume the firm to be constrained by arm's length limits, but to be unaware of the effects of its actions on the limits.
